## Use in other projects

The dataset has been used for various purposes, including:

* Fine-tuning different large language models.
* Fine-tuning different dialogue models, also known as conversational AI systems, including the Conversational Inference Machine (CIMi)  and Conversational Internal Language (COIL) models developed by OpenAI.
* Fine-tuning different machine translation models. This application is particularly important given that the dataset includes multiple languages.
* Conducting research on new problems in machine learning and natural language understanding. For instance, some works used this dataset to study the effects of language models on cognitive biases.

In addition to being used for fine-tuning, this dataset has also been used to train new models. For example, the authors of Ref. proposed training a dialogue model named GPT-J from scratch on this dataset.

In 2022, OpenAI was accused of having its dataset's contributors do the work of finding good prompts, so the model itself could be trained with "high quality" data. It was reported that the model was trained using the first 100 results for given prompts from the prompt tuning process.

The above was a simple Caesar cipher decryption, which replaces each letter with the one that's 3 letters after it in the alphabet (for example A->D, W->Z). For example, dolfhv would become '123456' and dgyhqwxuhv would become '789'. If the encrypted string is shorter than the range of letters it can reach through Caesar decryption, the remaining letters can just loop around the alphabet, like how Z->A.

If there are any letters in the encrypted string outside the ASCII character set, you just ignore those letters. It will depend on the assumptions the user meant for you to have when decrypting the ciphertext.
